> Our chef Mimi is a bit of a globetrotter and finds inspiration wherever she goes. This delicious 20-minute curry is a recreation of a particularly memorable meal she enjoyed on her travels, and is guaranteed to transport you to the palm fringed beaches of Goa, India. Quick, simple and delicious, this recipe ticks all the boxes.

Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} and bring back to the boil on
high heat. Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and boil for ~{8-10%minutes}, then
drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pan with the lid on, off the heat.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and finely slice the @red onion{1}(finely sliced). Roughly
chop the @vine tomatoes{2%medium}(chopped roughly into chunks). Zest the
@lime{1} then chop into wedges.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add
the @chicken thigh{210%g}(diced). Stir-fry until golden, ~{3-4%minutes}, then
add the veggies. Cook, stirring, for another ~{2%minutes}.

Stir in the @Goan xacuti curry paste{1} (careful, it's hot!) and
@tomato puree{30%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @coconut milk{200%ml} and
tomatoes. Bring to the boil then reduce the heat and simmer, stirring
occasionally, until the sauce has thickened slightly and the chicken is cooked
through, about ~{5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no it is longer pink in the middle.

Add the @baby spinach{125%g} a handful at a time, simmering for ~{1%minute} to
wilt in. Remove from the heat and squeeze in half the lime juice. Taste the
curry and add @?salt{to taste} and @?pepper{to taste} if you feel it needs it.

Stir the lime zest through the rice then season to taste with salt and pepper if
needed. Share the rice between your bowls and spoon the curry over the top.
Finish with lime wedges on the side for squeezing over. Enjoy!